<TEXT>
the soviet union has hired a british advertising 
company to sell broadcast rights and corporate sponsorships for the 
first britishsoviet space mission scheduled for 1991 a newspaper 
reported thursday 
the new york times said the soviets have hired the saatchi and 
saatchi company the worlds largest advertising and marketing 
conglomerate to exploit the commercial opportunities of the juno 
mission 
the mission which will carry britains first astronaut into 
orbit from a launching pad in the soviet union will be financed 
entirely by the sale of commercial opportunities the newspaper 
said that includes the sale of space aboard the soviets mir space 
station for scientific payloads 
the times reported that more than 10000 men and woman responded 
to an advertisement saatchi placed in several british newspapers in 
late june that carried the headline astronaut wanted no 
experience necessary 
if the soviets are successful in this and other commerical 
ventures a soft drink or cheesburger may be advertised on the side 
of a soviet soyuz rocket while commericals to promote a sneaker as 
the official athletic footwear of the space product the newspaper 
said 
the soviet space agency glavkosmos two weeks ago gave space 
commerce corporation in houston texas the exclusive right to 
market its goods and services in the united states 
glavkosmos has signed commerical agreements with several western 
companies in march a japanese televison network paid the agency 12 
million us dollars for the right to send a correspondent into 
space in 1991 
the national aeronautics and space administration which 
administers the us space program does not accept advertising or 
payment from private citizens for flights 
in the past us space shuttles have carried some projects for a 
fee but that practice was canceled after the challenger explosion 
in 1986 that killed seven astronauts 
</TEXT>
