<TEXT>
for nearly a year this was a 
liberated village outlawed plo flags fluttered from light 
poles activists patrolled the streets slogans covered the walls 
and popular committees did the work of city hall 
no longer 
at dawn on july 5 israeli soldiers stormed the village of 5000 
people and reopened armyrun government offices which had been 
attacked and burned by rioters in january 
this is a test case we went in because salfit had been 
portrayed as a main center of the intefadeh or palestinian 
uprising said col udi sagey he referred to palistinian statements 
that the village had been liberated from israeli occupation 
of the 420 villages in the occupied west bank several dozen like 
salfit have declared themselves liberated 
sagey head of the armys civil administration unit in the area 
said he planned to reopen its medical center reconnect the 
telephones restore postal and agricultural extension services and 
resume construction of a new road 
the first goal of the intefadeh leaders has been to cut the 
ties between the israeli authorities and the people he said if 
the economic support to these people is greater maybe they will be 
less radical towards israeli authorities 
he said he hoped if normal life was restored in salfit it would 
have an impact on neighboring villages that depend on salfit for 
services 
since the start of the 19month palestinian uprising salfit was 
largely ignored by the army because it is isolated at the end of a 
singlelane road the village is only 18 miles northwest of 
jerusalem but it is in rocky hills far from main highways and 
jewish settlements 
in january palestinian rioters forced the closure of all 
government offices and activists bedecked salfit with symbols of 
independence red black white and green plo flags and a map of the 
wouldbe palestinian state on a wall in the town center 
popular committees made up of activists aligned with the fatah 
plo faction and communist groups organized underground schools 
medical services street cleaning and agriculture 
in short salfit became a microcosm for the independent state 
that palestinians hope they can achieve if israels 21year 
occupation is ended 
there is no higher voice than the voice of the intefadeh 
declared graffiti freshly painted on a wall where the army had 
covered over previous slogans 
rafaat 29 a blacksmith talking with friends at a shop on the 
villages main gamal abdel nasser street said there has been little 
resistance to the army takeover because about 200 activists fled 
into the countryside to avoid arrest 
we were liberated for a few months but now there is more 
tension because at any moment a soldier can stop you or arrest 
you said rafaat who declined to give his full name for fear of 
reprisal 
the streets still bear the evidence of past protests the remains 
of burned tires and scorched stones blocking part of one entrance to 
the village 
ahmed a 25yearold grocer said soldiers patrol frequently but 
there were some small acts of defiance he said youths had hung 
about 100 flags the previous night 
this was disputed by a soldier standing guard outside the new 
military encampment that sported an israeli flag he said there had 
been only two flags 
the town is so quiet now that we go on patrol with just our 
berets and no helmets he added 
about a dozen palestinians gathered at the civil administration 
offices one man said he wanted an entry permit to the west bank for 
a relative who lives in jordan another said he wanted a travel 
document to return to his job in the arab gulf 
yet another wearing a bandage to cover a head wound he said was 
inflicted by soldiers had come to get his id card that had been 
taken during a searchandarrest raid 
all were kept waiting several hours even though a reporter who 
entered the encampment found two army offices sitting alone in their 
offices let them wait for awhile said the guard with a shrug 
bassam abu maadi a doctor who lives in a spacious villa on the 
edge of town said palestinian activists and the army were watching 
each other carefully to see what would happen next 
it will not stop in salfit as long as the intefadeh continues 
elsewhere in the west bank it will not stop until there is some 
hope offered for the future said abu maadi 37 
during the course of the uprising he said three palestinians 
from salfit had been shot to death and about 50 wounded about 250 
had been detained at one point or another 
abu maadi said arbitrary actions and collective punishments had 
left a feeling of resentment toward israel 
he said that after a jewish settler was killed in the west bank 
in june soldiers came to his house broke the porch lights and 
smashed a front window 
i came downstairs and opened the door an officer hit me in the 
face without warning or comment he then ordered me to go to the 
school where everyone was being rounded up abu maadi said 
if i do something wrong i will accept punishment but this is 
punishing everyone 
</TEXT>
