<TEXT>
the associated press time magazine and nine 
journalists from other us publications are among winners of the 
1989 awards competition of the inter american press association 
the awards recognizing excellence in coverage of western 
hemisphere news will be presented at iapas general assembly oct 
912 in monterrey mexico 
latin american winners include journalists and publications in 
mexico peru colombia costa rica and argentina 
the associated press won the iapatom wallace award for an 
extensive series written by 23 reporters on the plight of 
abandoned children in the hemisphere the association said the 
articles showed the aps overall commitment to latin american 
coverage 
tom wallace was the first us president of iapa 
other winners announced wednesday are 
iapala nacion of buenos aires award time magazine for cover 
stories on drug problems 
iapatom wallace award for illustration david walters of the 
miami herald for photographs of disturbances in panama 
iapa tom wallace award for investigative reporting alfonso 
chardy sam dillon and andres oppenheimer all of the miami herald 
for a series on the panamanian militarys control of that countrys 
economy 
spot news richard boudreaux and marjorie miller of the los 
angeles times for coverage of nicaragua 
feature reporting roger cohen of the wall street journal for 
his article on trainsurfing children in rio de janeiro 
interpretive commentary john zakarian of the hartford conn 
courant for interpretive commentary for his series on central 
america 
iapajamaica daily gleaner award for editorial writing rick 
nichols of the philadelphia inquirer for an editorial on central 
america 
iapapedro joaquin chamorro award for freedom of the press 
collectively to the journalists of colombia for condemning drug 
cartels and for having suffered so much for their courage and 
convictions 
iapapedro g beltran top publication award in latin america la 
nueva provincia of bahia blanca argentina for support of the 
handicapped in the workplace 
iapaharmodio arias award for human rights mariela balbi of la 
republica of lima peru for articles on violence against innocent 
civilians 
also cited in the chamorro competition were daniel merle of the 
reuters news agency in buenos aires for a photograph of violence 
during an uprising at a military base el norte of monterrey 
mexico for coverage of toxic waste and electoral corruption la 
nacion of san jose costa rica for coverage of hurricane juana and 
el espectador of bogota colombia for editorials against drug 
cartels 
the winners were announced by roberto fabricio of the fort 
lauderdale fla newssunsentinel chairman of the iapa awards 
committee 
