<TEXT>
a horse that knows when its safe to cross 
intersections allows a blind former cowboy to keep his independence 
but the city says the man must clean up after the animal or lose the 
privilege 
george bradford 69 who retains about 1 percent of his sight in 
one eye has a year to persuade the city council to let him keep two 
horses blue rocky and buck in his back yard 
when bradford rides blue rocky through town the horse stops at 
intersections and doesnt move until traffic is flowing in the 
direction the horse is supposed to go 
in 1981 the city council granted bradford a lifetime zoning 
variance allowing him to keep the horses in town 
but inspectors reported in 1987 that bradford wasnt cleaning up 
after the horses and was bothering neighbors with the smell the 
variance was revoked and a judge fined bradford 100 the fine was 
thrown out on appeal 
last month a judge gave bradford a year to change the councils 
mind or move the horses 
now hopefully what were doing is right said mayor ernest 
thompson as far as being unfair hes the one whos being unfair 
to his neighbors 
bradford said the neighbor behind the complaints is eddie 
wallace who wanted to sell his house next door but was afraid 
bradfords horses would lower property values 
wallace is not on speaking terms with bradford nor with reporters 
i dont want to say nothing about that crap no bye he 
said hanging up 
bradford who likes to smoke handrolled cigarettes and reminisce 
about the days when he worked as a cowboy in texas and new mexico 
had to stop working in 1964 because of retinitis pigmentosa a 
hereditary degenerative eye disease 
but bradford likes to ride blue rocky the two miles to downtown 
artesia across six intersections with stoplights 
he could see better about 10 years ago when he got blue rocky 
and started leading the horse on his walks into town when bradford 
heard traffic going in the direction he was walking that meant the 
light had turned green and he would cross the intersection 
now the horse decides when its time to cross 
he automatically stops anyhow at any intersection bradford 
said i guarantee you he wont go unless the traffic is going my 
way whether he can read the light is the 64 question 
other times bradford rides his horse into the hills west of his 
house 
you know i can get kind of down and out because i cant work 
and get on that old horse and ride five or six miles and hey i got 
a different outlook on life all of a sudden bradford said im 
completely independent 
he shudders at the thought of losing his horses 
oh i suppose somebody could take me places but you have to go 
back when they want to go back you know youre not independent 
</TEXT>
