<TEXT>
the authenticity of 19 superman collages by andy 
warhol has been called into question by two comic book experts who 
say the superman cutouts didnt appear in print until years after 
the date on the artworks 
either they were misdated or somebody has made some work that 
is not what it purports to be said robert miller a new york art 
dealer who owns 18 of the collages 
the discrepancy was detected by comic book experts arlen schumer 
and richard sheinaus during independent visits to a warhol 
retrospective at the museum of modern art in new york which ran 
from feb 6 to may 2 
schumer said in a telephone interview monday he was looking in 
the exhibition catalog at an untitled superman collage dated 
196061 when he recognized the inking style of the artist who did 
the cartoon panel 
i remembered that jack abel did not start inking superman until 
the late 1960s maybe 1969 and i thought hold it something is 
wrong here 
when i met sheinaus a month later he said did you notice 
anything funny about the warhol exhibition schumer said i 
looked him right in the eye and said one has got to be a fraud 
he said you wont believe this but there are about 15 of 
them 
the series of 19 collages has been estimated to be worth about 5 
million each piece was signed twice and dated 196061 the dc 
comics they came from like supermans greatest blunder 1968 
and muto vs the man of tomorrow 1966 sold for 12 cents each 
seven of the collages cutouts from original comic books that 
were pasted on paper and splattered with red or blue paint were on 
display during the moma retrospective six were loaned by miller 
