<TEXT>
paula r cooper convicted of a murder 
committed when she was 15 cannot be executed the indiana supreme 
court ruled today 
the court unanimously upheld coopers conviction in the 1985 
stabbing death of an elderly bible teacher but said she should be 
sentenced to 60 years in prison 
coopers case has drawn international attention and in 1987 pope 
john paul ii appealed for mercy on her behalf 
the court based its decision on a 1987 change in indiana law 
raising the minimum age for a death penalty defendant from 10 to 16 
and on a 1988 us supreme court decision barring executions of 
juveniles under 16 at the time of the crime 
but the court said although the law was compelling this is a 
difficult conclusion to reach because of the gruesome nature of 
coopers acts 
we won im elated relieved said coopers attorney william 
touchette im very happy for paula im just so relieved that 
this is over it was not an easy case 
cooper pleaded guilty to the stabbing death of ruth e pelke 78 
a retired bible teacher in gary according to court records pelke 
was stabbed 33 times after cooper and three friends broke into her 
home to get money and jewelry 
the three other young women received prison terms ranging from 25 
to 60 years for their roles in the crime 
cooper now 18 is an inmate at the indiana womens prison in 
indianapolis 
