cooper as the figurehead of their campaign against capital 
punishment amnesty international and the american civil liberties 
union have also pleaded on her behalf 
in march an italian group presented a petition with 1 million 
signatures to united nations officials urging clemency for cooper 
and in 1987 the pope wrote to thengov robert d orr to ask for 
mercy for the young woman 
orr and current gov evan bayh have said they didnt want to 
intervene in the cooper case until the appeal was resolved 
in todays opinion the supreme court concluded that executing 
cooper would be unfair because she would be the only person under 16 
ever executed in the state 
the general assembly after much debate in 1987 changed the 
minimum age for a death penalty defendant but made it clear that 
cooper wasnt to be affected by the change but the court said 
exempting cooper from the change is inappropriate 
now that indiana law establishes 16 as the minimum age for the 
imposition of the death penalty paula cooper would be both the 
first and last person ever to be executed in indiana for a crime 
committed at the age of 15 chief justice randall t shepard wrote 
for the court 
this makes her sentence unique and disproportionate to any 
other sentence for the same crime shepard wrote 
the state court also said that last years divided us supreme 
court ruling on an oklahoma case signals that four justices believe 
it is cruel and unusual punishment to execute a juvenile convicted 
of a murder committed before the age of 16 and one justice believes 
it is unconstitutional to executive a juvenile unless the death 
penalty itself identifies a minimum age for the death penalty 
while sparing cooper from the electric chair the supreme court 
said the circumstances surrounding her crime clearly support the 
next most severe penalty under the statute namely the maximum 
sentence of imprisonment 
cooper will be eligible to apply for parole after serving half of 
the 60year sentence 
