<TEXT>
nato today presented the warsaw pact with 
new proposals on reducing conventional arms and aircraft in europe 
two months ahead of schedule in a bid to accelerate a disarmament 
agreement 
the early presentation provided further evidence of our 
desire to achieve early results michael edes the head of the 
british delegation speaking on behalf of nato told a news 
conference 
presenting the proposal today instead of in september as 
originally planned gives the warsaw pact time to frame a response 
during an eightweek recess in the talks negotiations broke today 
and resume sept 7 
secretary of state james a baker iii outlined details of the 
nato proposal wednesday he said nato was recommending a ceiling of 
5700 combat aircraft and 1900 combat helicopters for each 
alliance the inclusion of an aircraft cutback complied with a 
longstanding east bloc demand 
according to nato data the warsaw pact countries have about 
9600 combat aircraft versus about 6700 nato aircraft 
the western proposal is based on a blueprint for deep reductions 
in conventional arms and troops in europe first unveiled by 
president bush at an alliance summit in may and subsequently 
endorsed by nato members 
bush called for military cutbacks that would fix the same ceiling 
of 275000 troops in europe for each superpower according to nato 
statistics that would require the united states to remove 30000 
troops from europe while the soviets would have to pull out more 
than 10 times that or 325000 
the proposal also foresees deep cuts in armaments with a 
proposed ceiling of 20000 tanks for each side and reductions in 
combat aircraft and artillery 
the decision to make the proposal was reached by a panel of 
senior north atlantic treaty organization officials in brussels on 
friday a us official in budapest said 
it complied with east bloc appeals that the presentation be 
speeded up 
the head of the soviet delegation oleg a grinevsky welcomed 
the nato proposal but said he was sorry it did not go further 
at first glance the proposal tabled by nato today has no new 
elements grinevsky said in a news conference 
rather it is a more detailed elaboration of the positions that 
were stated in brussels and only in respect of aviation and 
helicopters at that grinevsky said 
at a meeting in bucharest romania last weekend leaders of the 
sovietled warsaw pact praised bushs nato proposal and said an 
initial accord on reductions could be reached as early as next year 
however the east bloc summit did not produce any new concrete 
proposals on arms control of its own 
the bush proposal called for reaching agreement in six months to 
a year and for reductions to be carried out by 1992 or 1993 
in a statement issued at the end of the twoday bucharest summit 
the warsaw pact said the situation of the negotiations is such 
that the first understandings may be achieved already in 1990 
last week the head of the polish delegation to the vienna talks 
called on nato to submit the proposal before the recess rather than 
waiting until the third round of talks opens in the fall 
the soviet military bloc has a proposal on the table to reduce 
six kinds of weapons 10 percent to 15 percent below present levels 
by 1994 then add a further 25 percent reduction by 1997 before 
moving to purely defensive forces in the year 2000 
the soviet union has also begun unilateral troop withdrawals from 
eastern europe that are to reduce the number of soviet troops in the 
region by 50000 by 1990 
</TEXT>
