<TEXT>
illinois gov james r thompson the 
longestserving incumbent governor in the nation announced today he 
would not seek a fifth term in 1990 
near tears and with his voice wavering at times thompson told 
reporters that his decision was based on family and career reasons 
my wife and daughter said they would support another term but 
i wasnt ready for that thompson said at a news conference my 
family and their happiness and security is the most important thing 
to me at this time 
he added that he would enjoy the challenge of the private 
sector thompson also said he might seek another government office 
thats entirely possible he said i do not intend to 
retire from politics only from this office 
the 53yearold thompson a moderate republican who has served 12 
years was mentioned as a possible presidential candidate early in 
his career and as a vicepresidential candidate last year 
more recently speculation has centered on whether thompson would 
leave state government to accept a federal appointment or a 
partnership in a chicago law firm 
the speculation became increasingly intense over the past few 
months particularly within the republican party both secretary of 
state jim edgar and lt gov george ryan are interested in running 
for governor but both have said they would not challenge thompson 
democratic gubernatorial hopefuls have also awaited thompsons 
move as a guide to their own strategies 
thompson first burst into the national spotlight during his 
fouryear tenure as us attorney in chicago from 197175 when he 
sent several prominent allies of the late mayor richard j daley to 
prison on corruption charges 
passing up an offer to run against daley thompson instead 
claimed the gop gubernatorial nomination in 1976 and defeated a 
daleybacked democrat michael howlett by 139 million votes the 
widest margin in illinois history 
his first term lasted only two years because illinois was in the 
process of switching its gubernatorial elections to nonpresidential 
election years 
he was reelected to a fouryear term by another record margin in 
1978 and then twice turned back challenges by democrat adlai 
stevenson iii in 1982 by the narrowest margin in state history 
and again in 1986 to become the states only fourterm governor 
though titular leader of the state gop and a key backer of bush 
thompson has frequently been at odds with his fellow republicans on 
fiscal and social issues his political reputation is one of a 
pragmatic nonideological bridgebuilder evidenced by his support 
among traditionally democratic groups such as organized labor and 
his warm relations with some conservative chicago democrats 
thompsons most successful year in office may have been 1985 
when he played a key role in passage of landmark school reform 
legislation won approval of a massive infrastructure renewal 
program and landed the much soughtafter diamondstar auto assembly 
plant 
those promising achievements gave way to frustration in his 
fourth term as his efforts to gain approval of a state income tax 
increase were blocked by democratic house speaker michael madigan 
earlier this month he wound up signing a twoyear tax increase 
drafted by madigan and approved with mostly democratic votes over 
the objections of thompsons fellow republicans that set the stage 
for a potentially bruising battle over renewal of the tax in the 
months following the 1990 election 
</TEXT>
