the nation needs a comprehensive plan for 
controlling poison runoff into waterways from city streets farms 
mines and other sources an environmental group said thursday 
the natural resources defense council said some state and local 
governments have taken effective measures to reduce the pollution 
but the problem is growing worse in many areas because of inadequate 
national standards 
poison runoff is the leading source of pollution of at least 
half of the nations rivers lakes and coastal waters yet this 
problem has received a small fraction of government funds and 
attention said bob adler director of the groups clean water 
project 
adler said the runoff containing poisonous quantities of lead 
zinc copper phosphorus and agricultural pesticides and other toxic 
substances poses a potentially major health hazard for swimmers 
and fish and other wildlife 
this runoff has been more difficult to control than water 
pollution from factories and sewage treatment plants because it is 
diffuse and is given less federal attention he said 
adlers group announced the publication of a book based on two 
years of study of poison runoff that provides case studies of ways 
to combat the problem 
among its conclusions is that farms are the single largest 
contributor to the problem because of the use of fertilizers and 
pesticides that pollute surfrace and ground water soil erosion that 
carries excess nutrients and soil particles into rivers and streams 
and pollution from livestock 
were going to have to start thinking about regulating 
farmers adler said 
the book also said logging mining grazing and construction 
also contribute to the problem 
