<TEXT>
a public group charged thursday that the 
national science foundation uses a secret system ripe for abuse 
to evaluate grant applications from scientists and urged the agency 
to make the process more open 
public citizen a nonprofit advocacy organization told nsf 
director erich bloch that the system violates the letter and the 
spirit of various federal laws that are designed to make federal 
agency decisionmaking fair and accountable 
eric glitzenstein a lawyer for public citizen said at a news 
conference that the nsf for 14 years maintained a system of record 
keeping that blocked grant applicants from learning what had been 
put into their permanent file 
that meant unfounded allegations about a scientist were kept 
secret even if the information played a role in denying his grant 
application glitzenstein said 
the scientist cannot learn about the allegation cannot respond 
to it and has virtually no ability to appeal the denial he said 
anytime you have system based on secret reviews you have a 
potential for abuse 
the nsf is distributing about 18 billion to about 16000 
research projects for the 1989 fiscal year officials said 
the petition sent to bloch also alleges that the nsf has an 
inadquate system for dealing with potential conflicts of interest 
that may affect approval of an applicants grant applicants 
glitzenstein said arent allowed to know who is reviewing their 
proposal which means reviewers could include scientists who compete 
with the applicant 
that system also is ripe for abuse glitzenstein said 
the nsf changed its filing system last summer to allow future 
applicants to have have some access to grantreview records but 
those before 1988 remain closed he said 
lewis grotke nsf assistant general counsel said the agency 
would consider the petition but is under no legal obligation to act 
the agency he said has tried to develop a fair system to review 
grant applications 
individual scientists or research teams apply for grants to 
finance projects the nsf distributes the applications to experts in 
the field who evaluate the proposals and make recommendations 
glitzenstein said public citizen became involved after a 
university of texas geologist jon ervin kalb learned that two of 
his applications in the 1970s had been denied after reviewers 
discussed an incorrect and unfounded rumor that kalb worked for the 
central intelligence agency 
kalb and the nsf settled a lawsuit on the issue in 1987 the 
agency gave kalb 20000 in cash apologized and agreed to correct 
its records glitzenstein said 
</TEXT>
