<TEXT>
king fahd of saudi arabia called for 
islamic unity thursday as 18 million moslems ended the annual 
pilgrimage to their holiest shrines guarded by antiterrorism squads 
deployed after two bombings 
fahd made no mention of the explosions monday that killed a 
pakistani pilgrim and wounded 16 other people near the grand mosque 
in mecca the birthplace of the prophet mohammed 
our prayer is that the coming feasts will see the sons of 
the islamic nation in solidarity united and cooperating for the 
good of our causes and efforts to strengthen security spread peace 
establish justice and restore rights he said in a message 
broadcast by saudi radio and television 
as twilight descended around mecca the army of pilgrims prayed 
before they slit the throats of more than 1 million sheep cows and 
camels for eid aladha or the feast of sacrifice 
the meat traditionally went to poor saudis but since the 
discovery of oil virtually eliminated poverty in the kingdom most 
is flown to poor moslems in 26 countries 
the faithful then streamed down mount arafat to the scorching 
plain of mina and went on to mecca for final prayers during the 
pilgrimage or hajj 
waves of veiled women and men in white seamless robes signifying 
equality before allah took part in the prayers televised live by 
satellite to scores of islamic countries 
mondays bombings were the only incidents to mar this years 
pilgrimage and came amid an intensifying war of words with iran 
over the saudis limit of 1000 pilgrims for every 1 million 
population in moslem countries 
iran boycotted the pilgrimage as it did when the limits were 
introduced last year and cut its usual contingent of 150000 by 
twothirds 
saudi security authorities have detained an undisclosed number of 
suspects in the bombings the saudis have not accused any group or 
country although persian gulf newspapers pointed to iran iranian 
leaders denied involvement and accused saudi authorities of trying 
to discredit them 
tehran has used the bombings to strengthen its calls for the 
overthrow of saudi arabias royal family which it accuses of being 
antiislamic underscoring the historic rift between the worlds 1 
billion moslems 
irans estimated 50 million people are overwhelmingly of the 
shiite sect saudi arabias 12 million people like most moslems 
mainly are from the mainstream sunni sect 
the saudis cited vast renovation and construction projects in 
mecca and other holy sites for reducing the number of pilgrims 
they severed relations with tehran in april last year citing 
terrorism and subversion 
relations between the two countries soured by saudi support of 
iraq in the iraniraq war worsened during the 1987 hajj when the 
saudis charged iranian pilgrims started riots that killed more than 
400 pilgrims mostly iranians 
the saudis have spent billions of dollars modernizing the holy 
cities and providing all manner of services for what has become a 
logistical nightmare 
pilgrims once trudged in the sweltering heat on foot or by camel 
to make the hajj now they are transported free in 7500 
airconditioned buses hundreds of trucks and scores of helicopters 
the hajj which must be made at least once by all moslems who can 
afford it is the worlds largest religious congress it brings 
together arabian princes merchants from indonesia paupers from 
bangladesh and india 
each year moslems from soviet uzbekistan poland hungary 
spain senegal and other states join in chanting god is so great 
and to him we pay high tribute 
at mina each pilgrim throws seven stones at each of the three 
devil pillars a spot where moslems believe the devil tried to 
tempt abraham to disobey allah and refuse to sacrifice his son 
it was 120 degrees thursday when swarms of hajjis rushed to a 
mina gorge to stone the devil many were hospitalized for 
sunstroke 
during the hajj pilgrims must abstain from sex and may not 
quarrel cut their hair or even kill a fly 
