<TEXT>
the leaders of egypt india venezuela and senegal 
on thursday urged french president francois mitterrand to help 
organize a summit meeting as soon as possible between developed and 
developing nations 
mitterrand endorsed the proposal but said he would not seek a 
decision on the issue at a summit meeting of the leaders of seven 
major industrialized nations that starts here friday 
in a communique issued on the eve of the annual economic summit 
presidents hosni mubarak of egypt carlos andres perez of venezuela 
and abdou diouf of senegal joined with indian prime minister rajiv 
gandhi in saying 
we believe that steps must be taken to organize a summitlevel 
meeting as soon as possible with a view to discussing global 
economic and environmental questions of mutual interest 
mitterrand told the four that he was ready to take the steps 
necessary to bring about the project said presidential spokesman 
hubert vedrine 
but vedrine said mitterrand did not intend to ask the other 
nations participating in the economic summit west germany canada 
italy japan the united states and britain to decide on the 
request for a major conference among the developed and undeveloped 
nations 
this is not something for the immediate future vedrine told 
a press conference 
the four leaders representing nations in africa the mideast 
south america and asia said the proposed conference should mark the 
beginning of a consultative process between leaders from the 
developed and developing world 
the call for a summit among the leaders of the developed and 
undeveloped nations was the first publicized result of some 20 
bilateral meetings as well as informal lunchtime conversations among 
the leaders of 34 nations gathered here for the summit and the 
bicentennial celebration of the french revolution 
during their 15th annual economic summit this weekend the 
participants are expected to address the problem of the 12 
trillion debt that has stunted the developing worlds growth for 
more than a decade 
both mitterrand and treasury secretary nicholas brady are 
expected to push for partial forgiveness of third world debts in 
exchange for guarantees of repayment of the balance 
officials said mubarak discussed the issue with president bush at 
a luncheon at the elysee palace for almost three dozen heads of 
state and government attending the french revolution bicentennial 
events 
gandhi who sat next to margaret thatcher raised the issue with 
the british leader 
the developing nations leaders made their pitch for the ear of 
the richer nations at a time when the industrialized countries are 
steeped in a sense of economic optimism with the economic woes that 
dominated previous summits apparently under control 
summit host mitterrand to whom the communique was addressed has 
cast himself as a champion of poorer nations and announced in may 
