<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency said 
thursday it will add 52 military installations nuclear fuel 
facilities and nuclear laboratories to its list of the nations 
worst hazardous waste sites it gave no sign how much the required 
cleanups will cost 
many of these facilities are much larger and more complex than 
other superfund sites with wide varieties of of hazardous and 
radioactive wastes epa administrator william reilly said in a 
news release announcing the additions 
because they are federal facilities owned by various agencies 
mostly the defense and energy departments the cleanups mandated by 
superfund legislation will come out of the agency budgets the epa 
said 
you will see budget demands ballooning in future years as 
remedies are selected and the cleanup process the expensive part of 
the process kicks in jon cannon the assistant epa administrator 
in charge of the superfund said 
the list includes such facilities as the feed materials 
production center in fernald ohio the oak ridge reservation in 
tennessee brookhaven national laboratory in new york savannah 
river nuclear military plant in south carolina and the lawrence 
livermore laboratory in california 
the picatinny army arsenal in new jersey a 100yearold 
munitions testing and storage depot is also listed 
most of the sites slated for addition to the national priorities 
or superfund list are military installation 
the 52 sites announced thursday are in 26 states california had 
the most sites 10 followed by alaska and florida each with 
four of the 52 sites 41 belonged to the department of defense 
nine to doe one to the transportation department and one to the 
federal aviation administration 
all the doe sites contain both hazardous and radioactive waste 
except the bonneville power administrations ross complex in 
vancouver wash 
those eight doe sites are brookhaven in upton ny lawrence 
livermore in livermore calif the fernald center the mound plant 
in miamisburg ohio savannah river in aiken sc oak ridge in 
oak ridge tenn monticello mill tailings in monticello utah and 
the idaho national engineering laboratory in idaho falls 
so far the priorities list has 1224 hazarous waste sites 889 of 
which are final and 335 are proposed federal sites account for 115 
of that total with 41 final and 74 proposed 
epa says the list will evenually include more than 200 federal 
facilities 
once a site is proposed for inclusion that proposal is open for 
public comment usually about 60 days the list then becomes final 
according to epa officials at a news briefing the first step 
once a site makes the list is a period of study and negotiations 
lasting up to two years to determine a cleanup course federal law 
requires that actual cleanup work begins no more than 15 months 
later 
states and concerned citizens of the states as well as the epa 
may intervene to make sure the cleanup proceeds as scheduled 
the epa officials noted that the defense department had 500 
million in cleanup money in its budget proposal for fiscal 1990 but 
they refused to comment on whether the funds would be adequate 
we have not engaged in budgeteering relating to these 
cleanups said cannon cannon did say there were government 
accounting office estimates that the cleanup of doe facilities would 
cost between 80 billion and 115 billion 
the problem with time and cost estimates he said is we dont 
know what the ultimate remedies are going to be 
the epa says that to speed up the negotiations over the 
individual site cleanups it is asking to increase the number of its 
specialized superfund fieldworkers from 34 to 116 
