<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday approved new rules that will allow thousands of fm stations 
serving small communities to double their signal strengths and reach 
larger audiences 
the commission in a 30 vote said socalled class a fm stations 
could boost their power from the present limit of 3000 watts up to 
6000 watts 
the commission said the increased power will allow these stations 
to provide better service to their listeners without causing 
interference problems with other stations 
the commission also revised the distances by which class a 
stations must be separated from other stations in order to limit 
interference the current separation is about 65 miles 105 
kilometers while the new separation will be about 71 miles 115 
kilometers effective oct 2 
the area covered will be 40 percent greater said jay 
jackson an official in the fccs mass media bureau 
existing stations that do not meet the revised separation 
requirements will be grandfathered and will be allowed to 
relocate their antennas or request permission to use directional 
antennas jackson said 
there are more than 2000 class a fm stations nationwide the 
most numerous of the fccs seven classes of fm stations and those 
which have the smallest service areas the largest fm stations have 
signals with 100000 watts or more 
the commission said the small communities to which class a 
channels were originally allotted have grown over the years while 
the coverage of these stations has remained unchanged 
fcc chairman dennis patrick expressed concern about the 
commission being hit with a wave of applications from stations that 
need permission to boost their signal strength he said the current 
backlog was six months in processing such applications and that it 
could increase to 18 months under the crush of new filings 
he said he hoped congress will allocate additional funds to the 
agency to handle the expected glut 
but we should not forgo good policy decisions because it will 
strain bureau resources patrick added 
he acknowledged that some fm stations had asked that the rules be 
applied in a blanket fashion rather than on a selective basis 
patrick said a blanket approach would have caused too many 
interference problems 
we have not granted all the latitude that was requested he 
said 
to allow many stations to increase their power without delay the 
commission said it will publish a list of existing class a stations 
that will be able to boost their signal without interfering with 
other stations it estimated that about 500 stations will be on the 
list 
licensees who can increase their power with simple technical 
changes will be allowed to do so on or after dec 1 the commission 
said provided that the changes will not subject workers or 
residents to hazardous levels of radio frequency energy radiation 
</TEXT>
