<TEXT>
a house committee on thursday approved 
expansions in the medicaid healthcare program for the poor that 
would cost the federal government about 4 billion over five years 
the expansions would bring into the federalstate program many of 
the pregnant women infants and children who are not now covered and 
have no private health insurance 
the house energy and commerce committee also unanimously approved 
a nonbinding resolution calling for the medicare program covering 
catastrophic illnesses to be made voluntary saying congress cannot 
ignore the outrage among the elderly over the program 
rep henry waxman dcalif chairman of the panels health 
subcommittee said i think we need to make some changes in the 
catastrophic care program because so many people are upset 
i dont believe theres any other issue ive had people talk to 
me about said rep carlos moorhead rcalif 
rep michael bilirakis rfla who proposed the resolution 
called the program a catastrophic catastrophe under which many 
elderly citizens are being forced to pay for coverage they already 
have through their former employers and other sources 
the measures were approved 3013 as part of a huge 
deficitcutting package for fiscal year 1990 which begins oct 1 
the package now moves to the house budget committee 
the medicaid expansions would add about 183 million to the 
projected 38 billion cost of the program in the next fiscal year 
one change would require states to phase in over five years 
coverage of pregnant women and infants with incomes of up to 185 
percent of the federal poverty level the requirement would begin at 
130 percent of poverty by april 1990 which is what the bush 
administration has proposed but would rise to 185 percent by july 
1 1993 
a similar expansion has been proposed in the senate 
the committee shot down an attempt by rep sonny callahan 
rala to protect states like his own where the median income is 
low and a large proportion of residents live below the federal 
poverty line he said that under the proposed expansion more than 
half of alabamas newborn children would become eligible for 
medicaid at a prohibitive cost to the state which shares in the 
cost of the program 
another expansion would phase in coverage of children in families 
with incomes below the federal poverty level beginning july 1 
1990 with children born after sept 30 1983 as long as these 
children remained poor they would be covered by medicaid 
the committee also approved a change in the way physicians are 
paid under the medicare program replacing the current fee schedule 
with a new one based on such things as the skill training and time 
required to perform a service the fee structure is intended to 
correct inequities in the current system that reimburses specialists 
like surgeons and ophthalmologists at higher rates than general 
practitioners and internists whose services are mainly cognitive 
the house ways and means committee has approved a similar plan 
