about 12000 striking siberian coal miners agreed 
thursday to return to work after the government agreed to provide 
better work and living conditions mine officials and strikers said 
the twoday strike began tuesday at all five mines in 
mezhdurechensk prompting communist party and coal ministry 
officials to rush to the western siberian town of 107000 to settle 
the dispute the communist party newspaper pravda said 
strikers said thursday they were satisfied with government 
concessions that included better nightshift pay said victor 
ivanov a member of the government commission negotiating with the 
strikers 
strikes are becoming more common in the soviet union where they 
once were considered a western phenomenon brought on by capitalist 
exploitation of workers strikes used to be brutally repressed and 
hushed up but this year miners strikes have generally ended within 
days with government concessions 
nightshift workers at the shevyakov mine began the strike 
monday and it spread tuesday to about 12000 workers citywide 
pravda said 
the newspaper described the strikers demands sympathetically 
including calls for roundtheclock cafeteria service meat and 
sausage for underground workers free soap one free towel per month 
and a quilted jacket in winter 
the strikers 30 demands included economic independence for the 
mines extended vacations for underground workers and improved food 
and housing the labor daily trud reported 
calls for greater financial independence of individual mines and 
for increased nightshift pay were among those immediately granted 
said alexander kolmagorov a worker at the shevyakov mine 
requests for better food supplies and housing will take more 
time kolmagorov said by telephone from the mines strike 
headquarters 
people are back at work ivanov said all their demands are 
legal and are being decided most of them are satisfied but some 
will take time 
trud said the demands resulted from long years of neglect by 
authorities interested only in coal production and not in the 
miners needs 
mezhdurechensk about 1600 miles southwest of moscow produces 
30 million tons of highquality coal per year trud said 
in a bitter letter trud published in january mezhdurechensk 
miners complained that 10000 families are waiting for apartments 
hospitals and clinics are as crowded as anthills with patients 
