<TEXT>
a house committee voted thursday to levy 
licensing fees on hamradio operators and satellitelaunching 
companies and to increase fees on communications businesses to help 
reduce the federal budget deficit by 50 million 
the house energy and commerce committee also voted to outlaw 
obscene dialaporn messages on interstate and intrastate telephone 
calls and to restrict access to indecent dialaporn messages 
it adopted a new fairness doctrine that requires broadcasters to 
air opposing views on controversial public issues 
the committee attached the dialaporn and fairness doctrine 
motions to a budget reconciliation bill the 50 million in 
increased fees were to help congress meet the 110 billion deficit 
limit established by the grammrudman deficitreduction law for 
fiscal 1990 
under the committees bill existing licensing fees charged by 
the federal communications commission will go up an average of 126 
percent 
seventeen communications areas that were exempted will have fees 
for the first time ranging from 30 for an amateur radio license to 
70000 for a permit to launch a satellite said committee spokesman 
mike connolly 
fcc fines that have not been changed since 1934 also will be 
increased connolly said 
he said the vast majority of the 50 million will come from 
new fees with about a third of the money coming from private radio 
operations such a rural radio national paging services offshore 
radio and mobile and cellular phones 
minimum fees in nearly all cases will be 30 as opposed to 5 
currently the 70000 for satellites is the maximum other fees 
include a 6760 fee for a telephone company that requested an fcc 
hearing 
the dialaporn provision is in response to a supreme court 
ruling last month that invalidated a 1988 law that had outlawed the 
2 billion dialaporn business 
the court said indecent speech was protected by the constitution 
but that obscene speech was not 
the court since 1973 has defined obscenity as a work that is 
patently offensive purient and has no serious literary artistic 
political or scientific value 
connolly said the committees action takes the ruling of the 
court and works with those constitutional restraints it bans 
obsecne speech and it regulates indecent speech 
the bill requires telephone companies to block dialaporn calls 
to their customers lines unless a customer formally asks to have 
access to the service 
the fairness doctrine was added only after the committee voted 
358 against an amendment by rep tom tauke riowa to strip the 
provision from the bill 
tauke said the fairness doctrine a set of guidelines the fcc 
repealed in 1987 was unnecessary unconstitutional and made the 
bill veto bait at the white house 
the house and senate commerce committees both passed fairness 
doctrine bills in april president bush has indicated he would veto 
a fairness doctrine law and fairness doctrine proponents were not 
assured of enough votes to override a veto 
