had to cross picket lines to see their doctors thursday as 1300 
nurses began striking for higher wages and guaranteed hours 
the strike left group health cooperative of puget sound with a 
nonunion staff capable of handling only onefifth of the normal 
patient load at its three hospitals 
about 130 patients were moved to other hospitals and 72 remained 
said phil nudelman the health maintenance organizations executive 
vice president and chief operating officer 
