<TEXT>
the us economy shouldnt fall into a recession 
any time soon but growth will continue to slow through 1990 making 
profits more elusive for some businesses a private research group 
predicts 
the conference boards economic forum which is made up of 15 
economists said wednesday it expects slower economic growth to 
restrict productivity gains and raise production costs for many 
companies 
in addition the economists predicted the recent strengthening of 
the dollar if sustained could reduce prices and curtail demand for 
usproduced internationally traded goods the forum said 
the combination of downward pressure on prices and upward 
pressure on costs makes lower profits inevitable the forum said 
in a statement how far corporate earnings are squeezed depends on 
the strength of economic activity 
the forum however said it was not looking for a recession 
the conference board group predicted tighter profit margins for 
the paper chemicals and automobile industries but it said the 
outlook was more encouraging for industries such as retail apparel 
and textiles packaged foods petroleum banks and thrifts airlines 
and health care 
