the european commission has unveiled a 
new draft european company statute aimed at easing business in the 
future single european market 
the new draft announced wednesday is a watereddown version of 
the initial proposal which britain had strongly opposed 
eec internal market commissioner martin bangemann said however 
the statute aims to ensure that workers will be involved in 
corporate decisionmaking although this had raised britains main 
objection 
there will be no european company without a definition of the 
place of workers in it and in which way they participate in 
decisions bangemann said 
the proposal which has to be approved by the 12 member countries 
of the european economic community gives companies the choice of 
creating a european company bangemann said without forcing them to 
and without replacing national company statutes 
companies could create a european company through a merger a 
holding company or a common subsidiary provided that at least two 
of them have their headquarters in different member countries 
bangemann explained 
the new proposal lowers the minimum capital of a european company 
to 100000 european currency units or around 110000 to allow 
small and mediumsized companies to choose the new european statute 
the draft also contains tax incentives by allowing companies to 
offset losses in one member country against profits in another 
although bangemann said the european commission did not want the 
provision to be reserved only for companies choosing a european 
statute 
the provisions on employee participation would allow eec 
countries rather than companies to choose which model to adopt 
this is a change from an earlier proposal which gave companies the 
choice 
the commission the eecs executive body is offering three 
options appointing workers to supervisory boards following the west 
german example workers committees as used in france belgium 
italy and the netherlands or other models chosen in consultation 
with the companies concerned 
bangemann said member countries could allow companies to choose 
between the three models or limit the choice to one model he said 
west germany for example could limit the choice to the first 
option to remain in line with west german law 
