<TEXT>
when geo a hormel amp co meatpackers were 
threatening to strike nearly four years ago two reporters bet on 
how long the strike would last 
paul klauda said more than 10 days dave hage said one day or 
less thinking the strike would never happen 
i thought they would realize before they came to the brink that 
the strike would be a failure and that they wouldnt strike hage 
said 
he was wrong 
the bitter strike in austin minn lasted for months and 
provided hage and klauda both reporters for the star tribune in 
minneapolis with enough drama to fill a nearly 400page book 
no retreat no surrender labors war at hormel published in 
june by william morrow amp co inc is one of several books about the 
strike due on the market this year 
there were so many strands that went beyond just a normal 
labormanagement fight it wasnt just another strike said 
klauda who teamed with hage to follow the battle for the star 
tribune 
the walkouts intriguing ingredients included the presence of a 
fortune 500 company in a small southern minnesota town the 
halfcentury of labor peace hormel had enjoyed the benign history 
of the austin union which struck for three days in 1933 and the 
locals hiring of flamboyant union consultant ray rogers known for 
organizing jp stevens textile mills in the south and more 
recently helping eastern airlines strikers in their battle with 
management 
you just stumbled across one great story after another said 
hage and there just wasnt time to go back and revisit those 
people to explore a certain accusation or to get to know a certain 
person better because tomorrow or sunday theres always another 
news story to write 
for a time the strike was one of the nations top labor stories 
while other plants in the hormel chain agreed to wage concessions 
workers in austin decided to fight a proposed wage cut more than 
1400 union members walked off their jobs on aug 17 1985 
local p9 of the united food and commercial workers objected to a 
profitable company imposing a wage cut hormel said the cut was 
needed for the company to stay competitive 
since the strike ended the maker of spam luncheon meat cure 81 
ham and black label bacon has reported two consecutive years of 
record earnings continuing a fiveyear stretch of increasing 
profits 
hage and klauda said the strike symbolized worker anxiety about 
concessions in the 1980s but they concluded it failed to turn the 
tide partly because events in a town of 23000 werent going to 
reverse nationwide economic forces 
youre not going to overturn the high unemployment rate hage 
said youre not going to overturn all these trends in the 
meatpacking industry that involve nonunion competitors and falling 
redmeat consumption 
in their book hage and klauda trace the roots of the strike the 
first against hormel since the austin walkout 52 years before the 
reporters found it ironic that hormel with a history of good labor 
relations and innovations such as profitsharing dating to the 
1930s was the target of such bitterness 
