whose book on the strike packing it in the hormel strike 
198586 was published in april by kirwin amp sons publishing inc 
of st paul 
fahey concludes hormel was the wrong target for a meatpackers 
strike and that guyette was on an ego trip 
jim guyette had a very strong ego and he ran into another ego 
just as strong dick knowlton hormels president board chairman 
and chief executive officer fahey said thing was knowlton 
had more horses 
another book on strike at hormel takes a prostrike side 
and offers an insiders account according to its author hardy 
green the book will be published this fall by temple university 
press of philadelphia 
green worked for rogers new yorkbased corporate campaign and 
was in austin for much of the strike he disputes claims that 
guyette was on a power trip 
anyone who was in austin could see this was not the strike of 
one person he said it could never be the strike of one person 
leading a bunch of zombies because these people went all over the 
country 
three years since the strike ended there are signs that wounds 
are healing in austin hormel has notified 35 of 442 former strikers 
on a preferential hiring list that they will be called back to work 
by july 24 the company also held an employee appreciation picnic in 
austin that attracted more than 5000 
but some scars remain you almost wonder whether some day 
grandkids are going to look back and say which side were you 
on hage said 
