mccaw cellular communications inc is 
discussing a 12750 per share buyout offer for lin broadcasting 
corp that would give lin shareholders stock in mccaw the companies 
said thursday 
a mccaw spokesman said the new cash and common stock offer 
replaces the 110 per share cash offer mccaw made for lin on monday 
following a new york court settlement unfavorable to lin that offer 
was to expire july 21 
the new offer raises to 62 billion the total amount mccaw would 
have to spend to acquire the 902 percent of lins 539 million 
shares that it does not already own the 110 a share offer was 
worth 536 billion 
if the kirkland washbased mccaws takeover attempt is 
successful it would solidify mccaws position as the nations 
largest cellular telephone company 
the new offer came after lin complained that the 110 per share 
offer was less than what mccaw believes lin is worth 
the offer of 110 per share is gone negotiations led to a 
higher price potential said steven bruce of abernathy macgregor 
mccaws outside public investor relations counsel in new york 
he said the price was upped in an attempt to reach a friendly 
transaction 
negotiations resumed between the two companies advisers on 
tuesday 
bruce said the cash portion of the new offer could be higher than 
110 per share mccaw had originally bid 120 per share for mccaw 
the amount of mccaw that would be held by lin will be determined 
by the final cash offer and the price of mccaw stock on the day a 
deal is closed bruce said it is not clear if the class a common 
stock would be new stock or existing shares he said the shares 
will have voting rights he said 
the offer means participation by lin in mccaw he said when 
asked if lin wants participation on mccaws board he said 
everything is under discussion 
trading in both companies stocks was heavy on thursday they are 
each traded in the overthecounter market 
mccaw closed at 40 per share down 12 cents on a trading 
volume of 11 million shares lin rose 250 a share to 11675 on 
volume of nearly 18 million shares 
in a joint statement the companies said the proposal provides 
for each share of lin stock to be exchanged for cash and stock 
having an aggregate value of 12750 a share 
the companies cautioned that there can be no assurances the 
new offer will result in an agreement 
the announcement came a day after mccaw disclosed in a filing 
with the securities and exchange commission that mccaw and lin had 
recommenced negotiations through their advisers 
the new york court of appeals recently denied lins claims to 
certain cellular interests of metromedia co in the new york city 
and philadelphia markets 
