<TEXT>
a housesenate conference trying to craft a 
savings and loan bailout bill adjourned thursday night after 5 
hours of bitter and fruitless debate over how to proceed on a senate 
compromise proposal 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady issued a statement that the 
administration would strongly support the senate offer although 
he said he wanted to review the details 
sen donald w riegle jr dmich the leader of the fivemember 
senate team suprised many house members by starting the session 
with a senate offer for a comprehensive compromise and asking them 
to consider it overnight or over the weekend 
but the huge 94member house delegation was unable to respond 
because its leader rep henry b gonzalez dtexas has divided the 
delegation into platoons of between 20 and 30 members each with 
jurisdiction over part of the bill 
house delegates responded to riegle by voting to put the senate 
offer aside and proceeded to try to tackle the massive sampl bill 
issue by issue as senators sat rolling their eyes 
the house side made proposals on capital standards and funding 
essentially mirroring the original house bill but the senate 
refused to consider them 
at the end of the session shortly after 8 pm the only thing 
the two sides could agree on was a motion to meet at 10 am friday 
and try again 
riegle explaining that each position in the senate offer was 
crossconnected with the others said the senate could not 
proceed as the house wished and could only respond to a package 
counter offer from the house 
i dont think were communicating here sen john heinz 
rpa said 
rep jim leach riowa said riegle had made a bold 
imaginative offer designed to seize the leadership of the 
conference 
meanwhile sen jake garn rutah released a letter written from 
hungary by president bush who expressed strong support for the 
administrations plan to keep sampl rescue spending out of the budget 
deficit 
its the first time bush has addressed the issue personally 
although brady has threatened to recommend a veto if congress fails 
to adopt the administration plan bush did not raise the threat of a 
veto in the letter 
the conference committee which held its first substantive 
session on tuesday is trying to resolve differences between the 
senate bill passed in april and the house bill passed in june 
both sides noting that savings and loans are losing at least 10 
million a day say urgent action is needed and are aiming to send a 
compromise to the white house for bushs signature before congress 
leaves on its august vacation 
among the key elements of the senate offer are 
acceptance of the houses plan to require sampl owners to risk 3 
in real tangible capital for every 100 in lending by jan 1 1995 
the senate bill had provided a laxer standard of 150 
adoption of the senate and bush administration plan to keep sampl 
rescue spending out of the budget deficit the house had favored a 
plan that would have swelled the deficit by 44 billion over three 
years arguing that it was a more honest way of accounting for the 
spending 
a compromise on junk bond ownership by sampls limiting sampls to a 
junk bond portfolio equal to 6 percent of their assets or twice the 
amount of their capital the house had wanted to require sampls to 
sell their junk bonds within two years while the senate bill has a 
more liberal junk bond limit of 11 percent of assets 
acceptance with modification of house provisions requiring the 
sampl industryowned federal home loan banks to subsidize housing for 
poor people and forcing banks and sampls to disclose their record of 
serving poor and minority people 
adoption of a senate clause guaranteeing federal home loan bank 
board chairman m danny wall the right to serve the two years 
remaining in his term the offer also retains walls authority over 
statechartered sampls the house had wanted to transfer that 
authority to the federal deposit insurance corp 
gonzalez complained that the offer was too vague and amounted to 
little more than a letter of intent he told reporters that the 
senators by proceeding with a broad offer rather than sticking to 
the conference agenda may wind up delaying ultimate enactment of 
the bill 
in a 6hour session tuesday legislators agreed to raise civil 
and criminal fines for bank and sampl fraud to a maximum of 1 million 
a day and the maximum jail term to five years 
