<DOCNO> AP890713-0307 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday denied a request by an 
italian company to block a chicago board of trade order that is 
forcing the firm to sell a huge quantity of soybean futures 
the lawsuit filed by ferruzzi trading international sa and 
ferruzzi usa inc both subsidiaries of ferruzzi finanziara spa 
sought the restraining order and a permanent injunction against the 
exchanges directive published reports have said the firm was the 
object of the directive because it was trying to corner the soybean 
market something ferruzzi spokesmen deny 
the lawsuit claimed ferruzzi had been irreparably injured by the 
board of trades order which it said would diminish confidence in 
the market and hurt us farmers 
but us district judge james zagel who denied the request for a 
temporary injunction said blocking the cbots order could cause 
harm to the public 
the preservation of procedures adopted by the board of trade is 
in the interest of the public zagel said in issuing his 
lateafternoon decision 
ferruzzis attorney james fox said he did not know whether the 
italian firm would pursue the lawsuit or seek monetary damages 
cbot chairman karsten mahlmann praised the decision he told a 
news conference late thursday that there were over 40 million july 
soybean contracts open and abnormally low levels of stocks available 
to satisfy the contracts which would have resulted in a number of 
defaults without the exchanges order 
he said the exchanges business conduct committee tried to 
promote the orderly liquidation of the contracts but not enough 
market participants responded 
during the hearing before zagel fox said the emergency order 
forced the italian firm to reduce its holdings of july soybean 
contracts by 20 percent on wednesday and another 20 percent 
thursday he said the order did irreparable damage to ferruzzi 
cbot attorney john e angle said the exchange had entered into 
discussions with ferruzzi officials and had asked them to reduce 
their futures contracts but they refused to comply 
board of trade spokesman raymond carmichael said previously the 
exchange would vigorously fight the lawsuit 
soybean futures prices rose sharply thursday in reaction to news 
of the lawsuit soybeans for delivery in july settled at 697 a 
bushel 11 cents above the previous days settlement the july 
contract skidded 39 cents on wednesday 
in two related developments the american soybean association 
called for an investigation of the board of trades directive and 
the minnesota agriculture commissioner asked the fbi to check 
whether board of trade officials may have benefited from the effects 
of the order 
the board of trade the worlds largest market for grain and 
soybean futures issued the emergency order tuesday requiring any 
player holding obligations to receive or deliver more than 3 million 
bushels of soybeans for july delivery to reduce those holdings to 1 
million bushels by the end of trading thursday when the july 
contract expires 
ferruzzis lawsuit said the company holds obligations to take 
delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans ferruzzi also is 
believed to own a large quantity of physical soybeans 
if it does not reduce its position in the futures market 
ferruzzi theoretically could force those on the other end of its 
futures contracts to deliver possibly causing a scramble for 
supplies that would drive the price of its soybeans up sharply 
ferruzzi has said it accumulated large soybean supplies to keep 
its processing plants running and to meet export commitments and 
that its large futures market position was a hedge against price 
fluctuations 
carmichael said the exchanges board of directors issued its 
order because it appeared there might not be enough deliverable 
soybeans available to satisfy all the contracts 
the board of trade did not mention ferruzzi in its order and has 
refused to further explain the reasons for its decision however 
rumors among market watchers have pointed to ferruzzi 
in issuing the order the exchange cited federal regulations that 
allow it take such action to ensure the orderly expiration of a 
futures contract 
the st louisbased american soybean association urged the board 
of trade to fully explain the reasons behind its order to soybean 
producers and processors and saying failure to do so would be 
another blow to the credibility of the board 
minnesota agriculture commissioner jim nichols on wednesday asked 
the fbi to investigate whether any board of trade officials 
benefited from the emergency order 
in a letter to fbi director william sessions nichols said it was 
possible that some bot board members who made the order held short 
positions obligations to sell soybeans and benefited from the 
price drop following the order 
exchange spokesmen would not comment on the developments 
but an exchange official who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
dismissed as sour grapes the complaints of traders who ended up on 
the losing side of wednesdays dizzying drop in soybean prices 
any time you have any sort of order affecting the market youre 
going to have someone complaining about it he said someone is 
always on the other side 
some traders said the exchange should have left the market alone 
to sort itself out others said the emergency order spawned 
confusion and public mistrust at time when the board of trades 
image has been tarnished by a federal investigation of suspected 
trading fraud 
exchange member james merritt a 22year veteran of the grain 
pits said soybean farmers a group the board of trade has been 
wooing for years felt betrayed 
they feel like why should they try to legitimately hedge when 
the sanctity of the contracts are being questioned said merritt 
research director for merchants trading co 
theyre having second thoughts about this right now and i think 
i probably speak for the entire brokerage community in saying that 
its become quite an emotional issue 
</TEXT>
